for</i> ‘wild boar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","Altered form of English   Everenden  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Everenden","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: variant of   Evernden  . This form of the surname, which is quite rare in the US, is no longer found in Britain. Compare   Everton  .","History: Described as being from Kent, England, Walter Everenden (died 1725) was a colonial gunpowder manufacturer who ran a mill in Neponset in the township of Milton, across the river from Dorchester, MA. The first person to make gunpowder in America, Everenden eventually took majority interest in the mill and sold out to his son. The family, which later also spelled their name <i>Everton</i>, continued to manufacture powder until after the Revolution."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":39,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Everton was born in 1416, in Aspall, Suffolk, England as the daughter of John Everton. She married Reginald Edward Brooke about 1439, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1482, in her hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1416–1482":"1416–1482","1414–1482":"1414–1482","1419–1482":"1419–1482","1441–1474":"1441–1474","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","1454–1539":"1454–1539","1390–1416":"1390–1416","1482":"1482","1390":"1390","1414":"1414","about 1439":"umbes 1439","1445":"1445","Abt 1454":"umbes 1454","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1441":"1441","1474":"1474","1419":"1419","1539":"1539","1416":"1416","Suffolk Co, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stonham Aspall, Suffolk, England":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Aspall Parish, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","Aspall, Suffolk, England":"Aspall, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1416–1482":"1416–1482","1414–1482":"1414–1482","1419–1482":"1419–1482","1441–1474":"1441–1474","1445–Male":"1445–Kuollut","1454–1539":"1454–1539","1390–1416":"1390–1416","1482":"1482","1390":"1390","1414":"1414","about 1439":"noin 1439","1445":"1445","Abt 1454":"noin 1454","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1441":"1441","1474":"1474","1419":"1419","1539":"1539","1416":"1416","Suffolk Co, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stonham Aspall, Suffolk, England":"Stonham Aspal, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Aspall Parish, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, England":"London, England","Aspall, Suffolk, England":"Aspall, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1416–1482":"1416–1482","1414–1482":"1414–1482","1419–1482":"1419–1482","1441–1474":"1441–1474","1445–Male":"1445–Décédé","1454–1539":"1454–1539","1390–1416":"1390–1416","1482":"1482","1390":"1390","1414":"1414","about 1439":